an>-&nbsp;</span> <a href=3D"https://calcresource.com/geom-ngon.html#anchor=
-19">See also</a></div></div><a name=3D"anchor-3"></a><h3>Definitions</h3><=
p>N-gon is a polygon with N sides and N vertices. An n-gon, can be either c=
onvex or concave, as illustrated in the next figure. A convex polygon has n=
one of its interior angles greater than 180=C2=B0. To the contrary, a conca=
ve polygon has one or more of its interior angles greater than 180=C2=B0. <=
strong>A polygon is called regular when its sides are equal and also its in=
terior angles are equal</strong>. Having only the sides equal is not adequa=
te to guarantee that the interior angles are also equal. As demonstrated in=
 the figure below, many possible polygons can be defined, with equal sides,=
 but unequal interior angles. These polygons are called equilateral. A spec=
ial case of equilateral polygons is the so called star polygons. Any n-gon =
that is not regular is called irregular.</p><figure class=3D"image"><img sr=
c=3D"https://cdn.calcresource.com/images/geom-ngon-regular.rev.19d392a2ec.p=
ng" loading=3D"lazy" height=3D"534" width=3D"332"></figure><div class=3D"ad=
place" name=3D"AD_PARAGRAPH"></div><p>The simplest non-degenerate n-gon is =
the triangle with N=3D3. N-gons with N&lt;3 are degenerate. The digon with =
N=3D2 has two vertices and two edges. The two edges coincide in the plane, =
resulting in a shape that looks like a linear segment between the two verti=
ces. The monogon, with N=3D1, has one vertex and one side that connects the=
 vertex with itself. The following table presents the established naming co=
nvention for polygons, depending on the number of edges N:</p><figure class=
=3D"table defTable nicepad"><table><thead><tr><th>N</th><th>Name</th><th>Co=
mments</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td>monogon</td><td>degenerate=
</td></tr><tr><td>2</td><td>digon</td><td>degenerate</td></tr><tr><td>3</td=
><td>trigon</td><td>commonly called triangle</td></tr><tr><td>4</td><td>tet=
ragon</td><td>commonly called quadrilateral</td></tr><tr><td>5</td><td>pent=
agon</td><td></td></tr><tr><td>6</td><td>hexagon</td><td></td></tr><tr><td>=
7</td><td>heptagon</td><td>or septagon</td></tr><tr><td>8</td><td>octagon</=
td><td></td></tr><tr><td>9</td><td>nonagon</td><td>or enneagon</td></tr><tr=
><td>10</td><td>decagon</td><td></td></tr><tr><td>11</td><td>hendecagon</td=
><td>or undecagon</td></tr><tr><td>12</td><td>dodecagon</td><td></td></tr><=
/tbody></table></figure><p>Any n-gon with N&gt;3, can be constructed as an =
assembly of triangles. In fact the number of triangles required to construc=
t an n-gon is always the same and equal to N-2. Since the sum of interior a=
ngles in a triangle is constant to 180=C2=B0 (or <span class=3D"mjpage"><sv=
g xmlns:xlink=3D"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" width=3D"1.332ex" height=3D"=
1.676ex" style=3D"vertical-align: -0.338ex;" viewBox=3D"0 -576.1 573.5 721.=
6" role=3D"img" focusable=3D"false" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" ar=
ia-labelledby=3D"MathJax-SVG-1-Title">
<title id=3D"MathJax-SVG-1-Title">\pi</title>
<g stroke=3D"currentColor" fill=3D"currentColor" stroke-width=3D"0" transfo=
rm=3D"matrix(1 0 0 -1 0 0)" aria-hidden=3D"true">
 <use xlink:href=3D"#MJMATHI-3C0" x=3D"0" y=3D"0"></use>
</g>
</svg></span>), the sum of the interior angles in an n-gon, either convex o=
r concave is also constant and equal to: <span class=3D"mjpage"><svg xmlns:=
xlink=3D"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" width=3D"9.208ex" height=3D"2.843ex"=
 style=3D"vertical-align: -0.838ex;" viewBox=3D"0 -863.1 3964.4 1223.9" rol=
e=3D"img" focusable=3D"false" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" aria-lab=
elledby=3D"MathJax-SVG-2-Title">
<title id=3D"MathJax-SVG-2-Title">(N-2)\pi</title>
<g stroke=3D"currentColor" fill=3D"currentColor" stroke-width=3D"0" transfo=
rm=3D"matrix(1 0 0 -1 0 0)" aria-hidden=3D"true">
 <use xlink:href=3D"#MJMAIN-28" x=3D"0" y=3D"0"></use>
 <use xlink:href=3D"#MJMATHI-4E" x=3D"389" y=3D"0"></use>
 <use xlink:href=3D"#MJMAIN-2212" x=3D"1500" y=3D"0"></use>
 <use xlink:href=3D"#MJMAIN-32" x=3D"2500" y=3D"0"></use>
 <use xlink:href=3D"#MJMAIN-29" x=3D"3001" y=3D"0"></use>
 <use xlink:href=3D"#MJMATHI-3C0" x=3D"3390" y=3D"0"></use>
</g>
</svg></span>.</p><figure class=3D"image"><img src=3D"https://cdn.calcresou=
rce.com/images/geom-ngon-triangles.rev.08c3d6aed6.png" loading=3D"lazy" hei=
ght=3D"354" width=3D"218"><figcaption>A polygon with N vertices can be cons=
tructed by a minimum of N-2 triangles</figcaption></figure><a name=3D"ancho=
r-4"></a><h3>Properties of regular n-gons</h3><p>The focus comes to the reg=
ular polygons, hereafter. A regular polygon has all its edges equal and all=
 its interior angles equal.</p><a name=3D"anchor-5"></a><h4>Symmetry</h4><p=
>A regular n-gon features N axes of symmetry. All these axes meet at a comm=
on point, the center of the n-gon. If N is an even number, half of the axes=
 pass through diagonally opposite vertices and the remaining ones, pass thr=
ough the midpoints of opposite edges. On the other hand, if N is odd, all t=
he axes of symmetry, pass through a vertex and the midpoint of its opposite=
 edge.</p><figure class=3D"image"><img src=3D"https://cdn.calcresource.com/=
